WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.960 --> 00:00:12.120
Hi from Tokyo Japan, and welcome to Jeremy’s&nbsp;
IT Lab. In this section of our CCNA course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:15.760
we’ll cover the Spanning Tree Protocol&nbsp;
toolkit: a set of optional features that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:22.920
you can use to modify and enhance Spanning Tree&nbsp;
Protocol. This first video starts with PortFast,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:26.800
a handy feature that lets a switch&nbsp;
port skip the STP Listening and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:32.520
Learning states and immediately start&nbsp;
forwarding data when it’s connected.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:37.400
Here’s what we’ll cover. This video and&nbsp;
the next few will cover the STP toolkit.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:42.520
Starting with PortFast in this video, which&nbsp;
allows switch ports connected to end hosts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:48.600
to immediately enter the STP Forwarding state,&nbsp;
bypassing listening and learning. This lets the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:54.600
hosts start communicating over the network as&nbsp;
soon as they connect – no need to wait. Cisco&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:59.480
expects you to know four other features&nbsp;
in the STP toolkit as well: BPDU Guard,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:05.640
BPDU Filter, Root Guard, and Loop Guard. Feel&nbsp;
free to read these descriptions if you want,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:12.240
but we’ll cover them in the next few videos of&nbsp;
the course. So let’s get started with PortFast.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:16.880
First of all, what exactly is the problem&nbsp;
that PortFast solves? Let’s connect this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:22.960
PC and switch to find out. When an end host&nbsp;
connects to a switch port like this the port&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:30.080
becomes up/up but can’t send or receive data yet.&nbsp;
By up/up I mean the status of the port in SHOW IP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.720
INTERFACE BRIEF, as you can see here.&nbsp;
The switch’s G0/1 interface is up/up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:41.400
but any frames the PC tries to send are&nbsp;
discarded by the switch. And why is that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:47.000
it’s an STP designated port but will take a total&nbsp;
of 30 seconds before it enters the forwarding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:54.440
state. That is 15 seconds in the listening state,&nbsp;
and 15 seconds in the learning state. This leads&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:59.960
to a poor user experience. The user expects&nbsp;
to be able to access the network immediately,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:05.720
but for some reason it doesn’t work. The user&nbsp;
probably doesn’t even know STP exists. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:10.640
don’t have any reason to know it. They just&nbsp;
know the “the internet doesn’t work” for 30&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:15.920
seconds when they connect their computer. And&nbsp;
that’s frustrating. And worst of all, this wait&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:21.000
is totally unnecessary, because there is no risk&nbsp;
of a Layer 2 loop occurring between a switch and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:29.120
a PC. Loops can occur between switches because&nbsp;
of how they flood frames, but PCs don’t do that.

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:33.480
Let’s check out the process on a real&nbsp;
switch. Notice after I connect the cable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:39.920
into port 1 on this Cisco Catalyst switch,&nbsp;
the link light above it turns on. Each port&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:45.280
on a switch has a light like this, called a&nbsp;
link light, to indicate its status. The two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:49.720
blinking green lights on the bottom right&nbsp;
indicate that those two ports are active,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:56.240
and are sending and receiving data. But the link&nbsp;
light for port 1, which I just connected to my PC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.240 --> 00:03:01.760
is blinking an amber color. This means the&nbsp;
port is up and receiving data from my PC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:09.120
but the data is blocked by STP. My PC can’t access&nbsp;
the network yet. Finally, after 30 seconds, the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:15.520
light turns green, meaning it is in the Forwarding&nbsp;
state and is ready to send and receive data.

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:20.680
Now that we’ve seen the problem, let’s see how&nbsp;
PortFast solves it. Once again, I’ll connect this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:26.720
PC to the switch. When PortFast is configured&nbsp;
on a port, it immediately enters the Forwarding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:32.200
state when connected to another device – when&nbsp;
the port is enabled. So, it bypasses listening&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:38.320
and learning, and can send and receive data right&nbsp;
away without waiting 30 seconds. This obviously&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:45.000
provides a much better user experience: the&nbsp;
user’s device can immediately access the network.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:50.720
Let’s see PortFast in action on a real switch.&nbsp;
This time I’ve enabled it on port 1 of my switch,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:56.720
so let’s connect the cable. And as you can see,&nbsp;
the link light turns green right away – the port&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:04.360
is in the STP forwarding state and can send and&nbsp;
receive data immediately. No more 30 second wait.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:09.760
So, how can we configure PortFast? It’s quite&nbsp;
simple, but there are two ways to do it. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:16.040
first is in interface config mode with the command&nbsp;
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST. This enables PortFast only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:21.400
on the individual interface: the interface you&nbsp;
configured this command on. But you can also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.400 --> 00:04:27.960
enable it in global config mode with SPANNING-TREE&nbsp;
PORTFAST DEFAULT. Instead of enabling PortFast on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:33.960
an individual port, this enables PortFast&nbsp;
on all access ports. In most cases,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.960 --> 00:04:38.680
this will enable PortFast on all connections&nbsp;
to end hosts, but not on connections to other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:45.320
switches. This is because connections between&nbsp;
switches are almost always trunk links, since most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:52.120
modern LANs use multiple VLANs. But connections&nbsp;
to end hosts are almost always access links,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:57.680
since most hosts don’t need to send and receive&nbsp;
traffic in multiple VLANs. As we’ll cover in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:04.280
minute, it’s very important that you don’t enable&nbsp;
PortFast on ports that connect to other switches.

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:10.200
Let’s try that first method in the CLI.&nbsp;
I entered interface config mode for G0/1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:15.960
and used SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST to enable&nbsp;
PortFast. When you enable PortFast, you’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:20.880
see this warning message. This is related to the&nbsp;
point I just mentioned in the previous slide,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:27.000
so I’ll read it out. “PortFast should only be&nbsp;
enabled on ports connected to a single host.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:33.560
Connecting hubs, concentrators, switches, bridges,&nbsp;
etc... to this interface when portfast is enabled,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:39.760
can cause temporary bridging loops. Use with&nbsp;
CAUTION”. Basically, this means that PortFast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:45.520
should not be configured on ports connected to&nbsp;
switches, or temporary Layer 2 loops can occur.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:50.600
The entire point of the listening and learning&nbsp;
states is to make 100% sure there are no loops&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:57.000
in the LAN before a port moves to the forwarding&nbsp;
state. Because PortFast bypasses those states and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:01.520
makes the port start in the forwarding state,&nbsp;
it can cause a temporary loop if you enable it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:06.720
on connections to other switches. So, just&nbsp;
remember that PortFast shouldn’t be enabled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:12.800
on ports that connect to other switches. Okay,&nbsp;
in addition to that warning another message is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:19.040
shown here. "Portfast has been configured on&nbsp;
GigabitEthernet0/1 but will only have effect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:24.680
when the interface is in a non-trunking mode”.&nbsp;
So, even if you configure SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:29.560
on a trunk port, it won’t be active. By&nbsp;
default, it only works on access ports.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:35.160
Okay, after configuring PortFast on&nbsp;
the port, I used SHOW SPANNING-TREE&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:42.280
INTERFACE G0/1 DETAIL to confirm. Here’s the&nbsp;
command syntax. SHOW SPANNING-TREE INTERFACE,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:48.920
followed by the interface name, and then DETAIL.&nbsp;
And here’s the output of the command. Notice the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:55.480
line I highlighted. “The port is in the portfast&nbsp;
edge mode”. This requires a bit of explanation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.480 --> 00:07:02.000
There are two kinds of PortFast, edge and network.&nbsp;
PortFast edge is the kind we are covering in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.160
video. PortFast network is used for a feature&nbsp;
called Bridge Assurance, which is not a CCNA&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:15.000
topic. So, don’t worry about it. I just wanted&nbsp;
to clarify the meaning of “edge” in this output.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:20.240
Next, let’s try the second configuration method:&nbsp;
enabling PortFast by default in global config&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:27.880
mode. I’ve expanded the example network a bit.&nbsp;
SW1 and SW2 are connected by their G0/0 and G0/1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:33.360
ports, which are trunks, and their G0/2 and&nbsp;
3 ports are connected to hosts, so they are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:39.960
access ports. I’m only showing SW1’s CLI here,&nbsp;
but on both switches I configured SPANNING-TREE&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:46.440
PORTFAST DEFAULT. Just like before, a warning&nbsp;
message appears. Let’s read it. ”%Warning:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:51.000
this command enables portfast by default&nbsp;
on all interfaces. You should now disable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:57.240
portfast explicitly on switched ports leading&nbsp;
to hubs, switches and bridges as they may create&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.240 --> 00:08:03.440
temporary bridging loops”. Let me clarify the&nbsp;
part I highlighted. It says “all interfaces”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:09.320
but as I mentioned before it only activates&nbsp;
PortFast on all access ports, not trunk ports.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:14.840
So this warning message is a bit misleading. Now,&nbsp;
if you want to disable PortFast on a specific&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:21.080
access port after enabling it by default, you can&nbsp;
use the command SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST DISABLE in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.080 --> 00:08:26.320
interface config mode. You should do this if&nbsp;
you connect two switches with an access link,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:32.280
but that’s rare: connections between switches&nbsp;
are usually trunks. Okay, here’s that same SHOW&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:39.360
command I used before, looking at the output for&nbsp;
SW1’s G0/2 interface, an access port. It says “the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:45.960
port is in the portfast edge mode by default”.&nbsp;
So, PortFast has been enabled on these four ports,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:52.200
the access ports connected to end hosts. And what&nbsp;
about the trunks connecting the switches? I used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:58.240
the same command for SW1’s G0/1 interface,&nbsp;
and it doesn’t mention PortFast anywhere. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.240 --> 00:09:03.840
PortFast isn’t enabled on the trunk ports.&nbsp;
The key point to remember here is that, when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:11.760
you enable PortFast in global config mode, it is&nbsp;
only activated on access ports, not trunk ports.

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:16.600
We’ve covered how to configure PortFast on&nbsp;
access ports. Now let’s cover the topic of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:22.720
PortFast on trunk ports, because there are some&nbsp;
situations where it’s valid. The standard PortFast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:28.040
configuration commands only enable PortFast&nbsp;
on access ports. Those are the commands we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:34.640
just covered. SPANNING-TREE PORFAST in interface&nbsp;
config mode and SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST DEFAULT in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:40.800
global config mode. But in some cases you might&nbsp;
want to enable PortFast on a trunk port. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:47.360
network diagram above shows two examples. First&nbsp;
is a port connected to a virtualization server&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:54.600
with virtual machines, VMs, in different VLANs.&nbsp;
Virtualization is a CCNA topic, but we’ll cover&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.600 --> 00:10:01.040
it later in the course. For now, just know that&nbsp;
servers using virtualization often use trunk links&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:07.720
to connect to switches, instead of access links&nbsp;
like most end hosts. And the second example is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:14.160
port connected to a router via router-on-a-stick.&nbsp;
As we covered in the VLAN section of the course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.160 --> 00:10:19.800
router-on-a-stick is basically a trunk link&nbsp;
between a switch and a router. A router doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:25.280
flood frames like a switch, and it won’t cause&nbsp;
layer 2 loops. So, you can configure PortFast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:32.360
on interfaces connected to a router like this. So,&nbsp;
how do we actually configure PortFast on a trunk?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:38.240
It can only be configured per-port in interface&nbsp;
config mode. The command is SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:44.800
TRUNK. Let’s see an example in the CLI. The&nbsp;
command shows the same message we saw before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:50.320
warning that PortFast shouldn’t be enabled on&nbsp;
ports connected to switches. And here’s SHOW&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:55.560
SPANNING-TREE INTERFACE DETAIL, only showing&nbsp;
the relevant line since there’s no space. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:55.560 --> 00:11:02.080
says “The port is in portfast edge trunk mode”.&nbsp;
In most CCNA scenarios you will only need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:10.280
enable PortFast on access ports, but just keep in&nbsp;
mind that it can also be enabled on trunk ports.

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:15.080
Finally, before we finish up, I want to briefly&nbsp;
clarify ‘PortFast edge’, which I mentioned&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:22.320
earlier. To review, there are two PortFast modes:&nbsp;
PortFast edge and PortFast network. PortFast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:29.360
network isn’t a CCNA topic, so we’re covering&nbsp;
PortFast edge only. In modern Cisco switches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.360 --> 00:11:34.240
if you use the commands covered in this lecture,&nbsp;
the device will automatically add the EDGE keyword&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:40.560
to the configuration. So for example, if you&nbsp;
configure SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST on a port,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:46.320
in the running-config it will become SPANNING-TREE&nbsp;
PORTFAST EDGE. If you configure SPANNING-TREE&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:52.240
PORTFAST TRUNK, it will become SPANNING-TREE&nbsp;
PORTFAST EDGE TRUNK. And if you configure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:57.480
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST DEFAULT, it will become&nbsp;
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST EDGE DEFAULT in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.480 --> 00:12:02.440
running-config. You can use either version&nbsp;
of the commands when configuring PortFast;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:09.520
it doesn’t matter. The end result is the same:&nbsp;
EDGE will always be added in the configuration.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:14.040
As you probably guessed, if you want to&nbsp;
configure PortFast network instead of edge,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:20.160
you have to specify the NETWORK keyword in the&nbsp;
commands, like SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST NETWORK. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:25.560
also mentioned the command SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST&nbsp;
DISABLE before, but just note that it doesn’t use&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:25.560 --> 00:12:32.520
the EDGE keyword. It’s an exception. Okay, let’s&nbsp;
verify the EDGE keyword in the CLI. I configured&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:41.040
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST on SW1’s G0/1 interface. I&nbsp;
then used SHOW RUNNING-CONFIG INTERFACE G0/1. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:46.320
is a handy command. You can use it to view the&nbsp;
running-config for just the specified interface,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:53.360
instead of the device’s entire running-config. But&nbsp;
unfortunately it doesn’t work in packet tracer.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:59.240
Anyway here is the interface’s config. Notice that&nbsp;
the switch automatically added the EDGE keyword to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:04.520
the end of the command, even though I only&nbsp;
configured SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.520 --> 00:13:09.080
to summarize, just be aware that the&nbsp;
type of PortFast covered in the CCNA,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:15.320
the one we’re talking about in this video, is&nbsp;
called PortFast Edge. For the CCNA exam, you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:20.840
should probably be aware of both versions of these&nbsp;
commands: with and without EDGE. Their effect is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:26.480
the same. But keep in mind that if you’re doing&nbsp;
labs in Packet Tracer, the current version doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:33.600
support the EDGE keyword. So don’t be confused if&nbsp;
you try it in packet tracer and it doesn’t work.

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:39.040
Here’s a summary of the main points covered in&nbsp;
this video. When a host connects to a switch port,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:43.880
by default it takes 30 seconds before the&nbsp;
port can send or receive data. And this can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:48.800
be frustrating for users, who don’t know why&nbsp;
they can’t connect. PortFast allows a switch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:54.320
port to immediately enter the STP forwarding&nbsp;
state, bypassing listening and learning. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:59.120
the connected host can access the network right&nbsp;
away, making a much better experience for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:05.480
user. PortFast can be configured in two ways.&nbsp;
The first is in interface config mode with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:11.320
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST command, optionally&nbsp;
with the EDGE keyword. This enables PortFast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:16.680
only on the individual interface, and is only&nbsp;
active when the interface is in access mode,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.680 --> 00:14:23.320
not trunk mode. The second option is in global&nbsp;
config mode with SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST DEFAULT,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:29.360
which enables PortFast on all access ports. If&nbsp;
necessary, you can then disable it on specific&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:35.400
ports with SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST DISABLE. Just&nbsp;
remember that PortFast should not be configured&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:41.160
on ports connected to a switch, as it can cause&nbsp;
temporary loops. It should only be used on ports&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.160 --> 00:14:47.120
connected to end hosts, or maybe a router. And&nbsp;
keep in mind you can also configure PortFast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.120 --> 00:14:53.480
on a trunk port with SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST&nbsp;
TRUNK. This can be useful for router-on-a-stick&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:53.480 --> 00:14:58.720
or when connecting to a virtualization&nbsp;
server with VMs in different VLANs. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:05.200
that’s all for this video about PortFast.&nbsp;
I hope it was helpful. Thanks for watching.

